"The main paradigms in drug discovery represent evolving strategies for identifying and optimizing therapeutic candidates. They reflect shifts in biological understanding, technological capabilities, and empirical lessons from high attrition rates. While no single paradigm dominates universally, they often complement each other in modern pipelines.
technologynetworks.com

1. Phenotypic vs. Target-Based Drug Discovery (Core Dichotomy)
This remains the foundational distinction:
Phenotypic Drug Discovery (PDD): Also called empirical or function-first. Compounds are screened in cells, tissues, or whole organisms for desired functional or disease-relevant phenotypic changes (e.g., cell viability, morphology, or signaling) without prior knowledge of the specific molecular target. It captures system-level biology, polypharmacology, and emergent effects, often leading to better translational outcomes. Historically responsible for most first-in-class drugs; many "target-based" successes still rely on phenotypic observations for optimization or off-target effects.
technologynetworks.com +1
Target-Based Drug Discovery (TBDD): Hypothesis-driven and reductionist. Starts with a validated molecular target (e.g., enzyme, receptor, or protein) implicated in disease, then designs or screens for modulators (agonists, inhibitors). Dominant since the 1990s due to genomics, recombinant tech, and molecular biology. Offers mechanistic insight, scalability, and easier optimization but struggles with complex diseases and translational gaps. Analyses suggest only ~9–10% of approved small molecules originated purely from target-based assays, highlighting limitations.
pubs.acs.org +1
Contemporary practice often uses a hybrid or continuum approach, combining both for balanced strengths.

2. Structure-Based and Ligand-Based Drug Design
Structure-Based Drug Design (SBDD): Relies on 3D atomic structures of targets (from X-ray crystallography, cryo-EM, NMR, or AlphaFold predictions). Enables rational design, docking, and virtual screening. Powerful for optimizing binding affinity and selectivity.
pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov
Ligand-Based Drug Design (LBDD): Uses known active ligands (without target structure) via QSAR (Quantitative Structure-Activity Relationship), pharmacophore modeling, or similarity searching.
Fragment-Based Drug Discovery (FBDD): Screens small, low-affinity fragments (often <300 Da) for weak binding, then grows/links them into potent leads guided by structure. High hit rates for "undruggable" targets; efficient chemical space exploration.
nature.com

3. High-Throughput Screening (HTS) and Related Screening Paradigms
HTS tests large compound libraries (hundreds of thousands to millions) in automated assays. Can be target-based or phenotypic. Variants include high-content screening (HCS) for multiparametric phenotypic readouts.

4. Computational and AI/ML-Driven Paradigms
Emerging as transformative:
Virtual Screening (structure- or ligand-based) and in silico modeling.
Generative AI and De Novo Design: Models (diffusion, VAEs, etc.) generate novel molecules with desired properties.
Multi-Modal and Predictive AI: For target ID, ADMET prediction, patient stratification, and trial optimization.
Integrated with robotics for closed-loop discovery.
pelagobio.com

5. New Approach Methodologies (NAMs) and Human-Centric Models
Shifting from traditional animal models due to poor predictivity:Stem cell-, organoid-, and in vitro-based systems.
In silico simulations and digital twins.
Supported by regulatory momentum (FDA, NIH) for better human relevance and reduced attrition.
sciencedirect.com

6. Other Notable Paradigms
Drug Repurposing/Repositioning: Finding new uses for existing drugs (faster, lower risk).
Multitarget/Systems Pharmacology: Addressing network dysfunction in complex diseases rather than single targets.
pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov
Precision/ Personalized Medicine: Biomarker-driven, genetically stratified approaches.
Induced Proximity and Novel Modalities: PROTACs, molecular glues, ADCs, bispecifics, cell/gene therapies — expanding "druggable" space.
clarivate.com
Natural Product and Phenotypic-Inspired Innovation: Revived with AI for complex chemistry.

Current Landscape and Outlook (2026)
TBDD remains dominant in industry for its precision, but PDD and hybrids are resurging due to productivity challenges. AI, NAMs, and advanced modalities (degraders, radiopharma) are driving a potential paradigm shift toward more predictive, human-relevant, and efficient discovery. Success increasingly depends on integration: e.g., AI-augmented phenotypic screening with target deconvolution, or structure-based design within phenotypic workflows.
drugdiscoverynews.com
Challenges Across Paradigms: Translational gaps, polypharmacology complexity, data quality/bias in AI, and validation needs. No paradigm eliminates failure risk, but evidence-based combinations improve odds.
This framework provides a rigorous lens for understanding and advancing drug discovery. Hybrid, data-rich, and human-centric strategies represent the most promising path forward." 

